The viral video of a pall bearer who disposed of his Personal Protective Equipment (PPE) indiscriminately and unprofessionally after participating in the burial of Mallam Abba Kyari at the Gadu burial ground caught the attention the Acting secretary Health and Human Services  Secretariat, FCTA, Dr. Mohammed Kawu. Dr. Kawu speaking in a video said he contacted tahe Public Health Department of Health Secretariat immediately who immediately went to the Gudu Cemetery to properly evacuate abandoned PPEs left by those who attended the burial of the former Chief of Staff and the entire cemetery decontaminated. In a press statement he said they had also identified the men working in the cemetery who participated in the burial rites and were not properly kitted “ They will be traced and put in isolation, necessary tests will be conducted on all of them to determine their level of exposure. Nigerians yesterday on social media faulted the zero enforcement of social distancing at the burial ground and the indiscriminate disposal of PPEs by one of the pall bearers. Another video showed officials from the FCTA Public Health Department disposing abandoned PPEs and disinfecting the cemetery. Dr. Kawu said the administration has also taken steps to ensure that all future burials of victims of COVID-19 are conducted in line with protocols established by the Nigerian Centre for Disease Control (NCDC). He urged residents to remain as he assured that the administration was doing everything necessary to curtail the spread of the virus in the FCT. COVID-19: Ministers wear masks for briefings, healthcare personnel work without them Social distancing: NGO threatens legal action if Kyari burial party isn't quarantined How COVID-19 halted burial ceremonies